Midterm Decision

Conclusion

\[ \overbrace{\hat{Y}_i}^{\text{Final Exam}} = \beta_0 + \beta_1\overbrace{X_i}^{\text{Midterm}} + \epsilon \]

grades %>% ggplot(aes(x = Midterm, y = FinalExam)) + 
  stat_function(fun = function(x) (exp(3.113969+0.014276*x)), color = "red") + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(title = "Math 425 Final Exam Scores by Midterm Scores", 
       y = "Final Exam %", 
       x = "Midterm %")

With a p-value of 0.016, we can conclude that the slope is in fact significant according to the model. This shows there is a positive relationship because the score received on the midterm affecting how well you do on the final.

Personal Results vs. Class Results
library(ggrepel)

myMidterm <- 64
predFinal <- predict(results, data.frame(Midterm=c(myMidterm)))
predInterval <- predict(results, data.frame(Midterm=c(myMidterm)), interval="confidence")

# grades <- grades %>% 
#   add_row(Gender = "Male", FinalExam = predFinal,
#           Midterm = myMidterm, SkillsQuizzesTotal = NA)

grades %>% ggplot(aes(x = Midterm, y = FinalExam)) + 
  stat_function(fun = function(x) (exp(3.113969+0.014276*x)), color = "red") + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = myMidterm, y = predFinal, color = "red")) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = predInterval[2], color = "blue"), linetype = "dashed") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = predInterval[3], color = "blue"), linetype = "dashed") + 
  labs(title = "Math 425 Final Exam Scores by Midterm Scores", 
       y = "Final Exam %", 
       x = "Midterm %") + 
  scale_color_manual(labels = c("My Midterm", "Prediction Intervals"), values = c("blue", "blue"))

Based off the regression, it is predicted that I would achieve a 61% on the final. Given the std. error of the prediction interval, it is only possible I would receive up to a 70%. Because the final will be weighted differently, in this best case scenario, I would receive a 68% as the final grade. For this reason, I have decided to drop my midterm score and opt in to only retain my final score.

  • There appear to be some major outliers such as point 21 where the student got a 68% on the midterm, yet only received 8% on the final. It is possible this is an error or that the student stopped going to class and merely guessed on the final.
  • One data point was removed from the dataset because they received zeros on both the final and midterm. This is assumed to be a student who dropped the class before the midterm and took neither of the tests.
  • The data seems to have constant variance, however, the qq-plot is abnormal, suggesting that the distribution is not quite normal.
